## 3. Causal Decomposition

Break the system into stages or components so a failure can be attributed to one place. This is the backbone the rest of the framework leans on: each component is a row, each {{EXPERIMENT_UNIT_LABEL}} changes exactly one row, and `docs/evaluation/debugging-guide.md` maps symptoms back to these rows. A component earns a row only if a change to it could plausibly move a metric on its own.

Fill in the table for this project; the rows below are illustrative examples from different domains to show the shape.

| Stage / Component | What it does | Failure it can cause |
|---|---|---|
| Input preparation (illustrative, ML) | Turns raw inputs into the representation the model consumes | Bad normalization makes every downstream metric look worse, masking the real cause |
| Sample handling (illustrative, wet-lab) | Prepares and loads specimens before measurement | Pipetting or plate-layout error shows up as a treatment effect that is really position bias |
| Request scheduler (illustrative, systems) | Orders and batches incoming work | A greedy batching policy inflates tail latency while average latency looks fine |

Each {{EXPERIMENT_UNIT_LABEL}} should change one component in this table and hold the rest fixed (the central discipline of this framework), so the resulting metric delta is attributable. When a {{EXPERIMENT_UNIT_LABEL}} surprises you, walk this table top to bottom in `docs/evaluation/debugging-guide.md`.

Common pitfall: a "component" that bundles two independent mechanisms (for example, "preprocessing + augmentation") cannot be tested in isolation. Split it into two rows so each can be a separate {{EXPERIMENT_UNIT_LABEL}}.

